# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: consensus-algorithms
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] A **Byzantine fault** is a condition of a system, particularly a distributed computing system, where a fault occurs such that different symptoms are presented to different observers, including imperfect information on whether a system component has failed.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] A Byzantine fault is also known as a **Byzantine generals problem**, a **Byzantine agreement problem**, or a **Byzantine failure**.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] A Byzantine fault is any fault presenting different symptoms to different observers.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] A Byzantine failure is the loss of a system service due to a Byzantine fault in systems that require consensus among multiple components.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] The Byzantine allegory considers a number of generals who are attacking a fortress.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] The generals must decide as a group whether to attack or retreat; some may prefer to attack, while others prefer to retreat.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] The important thing is that all generals agree on a common decision, for a half-hearted attack by a few generals would become a rout, and would be worse than either a coordinated attack or a coordinated retreat.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] The problem is complicated by the presence of treacherous generals who may not only cast a vote for a suboptimal strategy; they may do so selectively.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] For instance, if nine generals are voting, four of whom support attacking while four others are in favor of retreat, the ninth general may send a vote of retreat to those generals in favor of retreat, and a vote of attack to the rest.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] Those who received a retreat vote from the ninth general will retreat, while the rest will attack (which may not go well for the attackers).
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] The problem is complicated further by the generals being physically separated and having to send their votes via messengers who may fail to deliver votes or may forge false votes.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] Without message signing, Byzantine fault tolerance can only be achieved if the total number of generals is greater than three times the number of disloyal (faulty) generals.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] There can be a default vote value given to missing messages.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] For example, missing messages can be given a "null" value.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] Further, if the agreement is that the null votes are in the majority, a pre-assigned default strategy can be used (e.g., retreat).
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] The typical mapping of this allegory onto computer systems is that the computers are the generals and their digital communication system links are the messengers.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] Although the problem is formulated in the allegory as a decision-making and security problem, in electronics, it cannot be solved by cryptographic digital signatures alone, because failures such as incorrect voltages can propagate through the encryption process.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] Thus, a faulty message could be sent such that some recipients detect the message as faulty (bad signature), others see it is having a good signature, and a third group also sees a good signature but with different message contents than the second group.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] The problem of obtaining Byzantine consensus was conceived and formalized by Robert Shostak, who dubbed it the *interactive consistency* problem.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] This work was done in 1978 in the context of the NASA-sponsored SIFT project in the Computer Science Lab at SRI International.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] SIFT (for Software Implemented Fault Tolerance) was the brainchild of John Wensley, and was based on the idea of using multiple general-purpose computers that would communicate through pairwise messaging in order to reach a consensus, even if some of the computers were faulty.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] At the beginning of the project, it was not clear how many computers in total were needed to guarantee that a conspiracy of *n* faulty computers could not "thwart" the efforts of the correctly-operating ones to reach consensus.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] Shostak showed that a minimum of 3*n+*1 are needed, and devised a two-round 3*n+1* messaging protocol that would work for *n*=1.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] His colleague Marshall Pease generalized the algorithm for any n > 0, proving that 3*n*+1 is both necessary and sufficient.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] These results, together with a later proof by Leslie Lamport of the sufficiency of 3*n* using digital signatures, were published in the seminal paper, *Reaching Agreement in the Presence of Faults.* The authors were awarded the 2005 Edsger W.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] To make the interactive consistency problem easier to understand, Lamport devised a colorful allegory in which a group of army generals formulate a plan for attacking a city.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] In its original version, the story cast the generals as commanders of the Albanian army.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] The name was changed, eventually settling on "Byzantine", at the suggestion of Jack Goldberg to future-proof any potential offense-giving.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] This formulation of the problem, together with some additional results, were presented by the same authors in their 1982 paper, "The Byzantine Generals Problem".
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] The objective of Byzantine fault tolerance is to be able to defend against failures of system components with or without symptoms that prevent other components of the system from reaching an agreement among themselves, where such an agreement is needed for the correct operation of the system.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] The remaining operationally correct components of a Byzantine fault tolerant system will be able to continue providing the system's service as originally intended, assuming there are a sufficient number of accurately-operating components to maintain the service.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] When considering failure propagation only via errors, Byzantine failures are considered the most general and most difficult class of failures among the failure modes.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] The so-called fail-stop failure mode occupies the simplest end of the spectrum.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] Thus, Byzantine failures can confuse failure detection systems, which makes fault tolerance difficult.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] Despite the allegory, a Byzantine failure is not necessarily a security problem involving hostile human interference: it can arise purely from physical or software faults.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] This kind of fault tolerance does not encompass the correctness of the value itself; for example, an adversarial component that deliberately sends an incorrect value, but sends that same value consistently to all components, will not be caught in the Byzantine fault tolerance scheme.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] Several early solutions were described by Lamport, Shostak, and Pease in 1982.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] There are many systems that claim BFT without meeting the above minimum requirements (e.g., blockchain).
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] Given that there is mathematical proof that this is impossible, these claims need to include a caveat that their definition of BFT strays from the original.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] That is, systems such as blockchain don't guarantee agreement.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] They use resource-intensive mechanisms that make disagreements impractical to maintain.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] Several system architectures were designed c.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] 1980 that implemented Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] These include: Draper's FTMP, Honeywell's MMFCS, and SRI's SIFT.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] In 1999, Miguel Castro and Barbara Liskov introduced the "Practical Byzantine Fault Tolerance" (PBFT) algorithm, which provides high-performance Byzantine state machine replication, processing thousands of requests per second with sub-millisecond increases in latency.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] After PBFT, several BFT protocols were introduced to improve its robustness and performance.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] For instance, Q/U, HQ, Zyzzyva, and ABsTRACTs, addressed the performance and cost issues; whereas other protocols, like Aardvark and RBFT, addressed its robustness issues.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] Furthermore, Adapt tried to make use of existing BFT protocols, through switching between them in an adaptive way, to improve system robustness and performance as the underlying conditions change.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] Furthermore, BFT protocols were introduced that leverage trusted components to reduce the number of replicas, e.g., A2M-PBFT-EA and MinBFT.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] Recent research addresses the scalability limits of traditional BFT implementations (which often incur $O(n^{2})$ communication complexity) by parallelizing consensus.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] For example, the Cerberus protocol maps data to a large, fixed state space to couple consensus instances with specific transaction sets.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] This allows BFT processes to run independently in parallel, enabling linear scalability relative to the network size.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] Several examples of Byzantine failures that have occurred are given in two equivalent journal papers.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] These and other examples are described on the NASA DASHlink web pages.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] Byzantine fault tolerance mechanisms use components that repeat an incoming message (or just its signature, which can be reduced to just a single bit of information if self-checking pairs are used for nodes) to other recipients of that incoming message.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] All these mechanisms make the assumption that the act of repeating a message blocks the propagation of Byzantine symptoms.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] For systems that have a high degree of safety or security criticality, these assumptions must be proven to be true to an acceptable level of fault coverage.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] When providing proof through testing, one difficulty is creating a sufficiently wide range of signals with Byzantine symptoms.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] Such testing will likely require specialized fault injectors.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] Byzantine errors were observed infrequently and at irregular points during endurance testing for the newly constructed *Virginia*-class submarine, at least through 2005 (when the issues were publicly reported).
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] The Bitcoin network works in parallel to generate a blockchain with proof of work allowing the system to overcome Byzantine failures and reach a coherent global view of the system's state.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] Some proof of stake blockchains also use BFT algorithms.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] Byzantine fault tolerance is a crucial concept in blockchain technology, ensuring that a network can continue to function even when some nodes (participants) fail or act maliciously.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] This tolerance is necessary because blockchains are decentralized systems with no central authority, making it essential to achieve consensus among nodes, even if some try to disrupt the process.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] Ensuring that an AI system behaves reliably and as intended, especially in the presence of unexpected faults or adversarial conditions, is a complex challenge.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] By accepting that components may fail, and further that frontier AI models may deceive, Byzantine fault tolerance has been proposed as an approach towards AI safety.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] Structuring AI systems as ensembles of AI artifacts or modules that check and balance each other leads to strong assurances that no single errant or deceptive component can easily steer the system into an unsafe state.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] , BFT-based systems are designed to tolerate up to one-third of faulty or malicious nodes without compromising the network's integrity.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] Instead of relying on a central authority, the network's security depends on the ability of honest nodes to outnumber and outmaneuver malicious ones.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] BFT is especially important in private or permissioned blockchains, where a limited number of known participants need to reach a consensus quickly and securely.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] These networks often use BFT protocols to enhance performance and security.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] For example, SAFEbus can achieve Byzantine fault tolerance within the order of a microsecond of added latency.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] The SpaceX Dragon considers Byzantine fault tolerance in its design.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] The Ares rocket avionics, now the Space Launch System (SLS), utilizes a triplex with an interstage of accomplish Byzantine resilience.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] The Orion spacecraft utilizes self-checking pairs to detect and mask Byzantine faults.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] In legislatures, civil societies, polls, statistical surveys, and so forth, systems that require a minimum supermajority threshold agreement greater than two-thirds are similar to consensus reflective of Byzantine Fault Tolerant -like characteristics.
[src:consensus-algorithms/byzantine-fault] By contrast, systems that operate on the sub-supermajority basis of simple majorities or a minority government could be vulnerable to Byzantine fault -like behavior.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] A fundamental problem in distributed computing and multi-agent systems is to achieve overall system reliability in the presence of a number of faulty processes.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] This often requires coordinating processes to reach **consensus**, or agree on some data value that is needed during computation.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Example applications of consensus include agreeing on what transactions to commit to a database in which order, state machine replication, and atomic broadcasts.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Real-world applications often requiring consensus include cloud computing, clock synchronization, PageRank, opinion formation, smart power grids, state estimation, control of UAVs (and multiple robots/agents in general), load balancing, blockchain, and others.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] The consensus problem requires agreement among a number of processes (or agents) on a single data value.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Some of the processes (agents) may fail or be unreliable in other ways, so consensus protocols must be fault-tolerant or resilient.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] The processes must put forth their candidate values, communicate with one another, and agree on a single consensus value.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] The consensus problem is a fundamental problem in controlling multi-agent systems.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] One approach to generating consensus is for all processes (agents) to agree on a majority value.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] In this context, a majority requires at least one more than half of the available votes (where each process is given a vote).
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] However, one or more faulty processes may skew the resultant outcome such that consensus may not be reached or may be reached incorrectly.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Protocols that solve consensus problems are designed to deal with a limited number of faulty processes.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] These protocols must satisfy several requirements to be useful.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] For instance, a trivial protocol could have all processes output binary value 1.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] This is not useful; thus, the requirement is modified such that the production must depend on the input.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] That is, the output value of a consensus protocol must be the input value of some process.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Another requirement is that a process may decide upon an output value only once, and this decision is irrevocable.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] A method is correct in an execution if it does not experience a failure.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] A consensus protocol tolerating halting failures must satisfy the following properties.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Eventually, every correct process decides some value.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Every correct process must agree on the same value.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Variations on the definition of *integrity* may be appropriate, according to the application.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] For example, a weaker type of integrity would be for the decision value to equal a value that some correct process proposed – not necessarily all of them.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] There is also a condition known as **validity** in the literature which refers to the property that a message sent by a process must be delivered.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] A protocol that can correctly guarantee consensus amongst n processes of which at most t fail is said to be *t-resilient*.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] In evaluating the performance of consensus protocols two factors of interest are *running time* and *message complexity*.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Running time is given in Big O notation in the number of rounds of message exchange as a function of some input parameters (typically the number of processes and/or the size of the input domain).
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Message complexity refers to the amount of message traffic that is generated by the protocol.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Other factors may include memory usage and the size of messages.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Varying models of computation may define a "consensus problem".
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Some models may deal with fully connected graphs, while others may deal with rings and trees.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] In some models message authentication is allowed, whereas in others processes are completely anonymous.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Shared memory models in which processes communicate by accessing objects in shared memory are also an important area of research.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] In most models of communication protocol participants communicate through *authenticated channels.* This means that messages are not anonymous, and receivers know the source of every message they receive.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Some models assume a stronger, *transferable* form of authentication, where each *message* is signed by the sender, so that a receiver knows not just the immediate source of every message, but the participant that initially created the message.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] This stronger type of authentication is achieved by digital signatures, and when this stronger form of authentication is available, protocols can tolerate a larger number of faults.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] The two different authentication models are often called *oral communication* and *written communication* models.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] In an oral communication model, the immediate source of information is known, whereas in stronger, written communication models, every step along the receiver learns not just the immediate source of the message, but the communication history of the message.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] In the most traditional **single-value** consensus protocols such as Paxos, cooperating nodes agree on a single value such as an integer, which may be of variable size so as to encode useful metadata such as a transaction committed to a database.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] A special case of the single-value consensus problem, called **binary consensus**, restricts the input, and hence the output domain, to a single binary digit {0,1}.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] While not highly useful by themselves, binary consensus protocols are often useful as building blocks in more general consensus protocols, especially for asynchronous consensus.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] In **multi-valued** consensus protocols such as Multi-Paxos and Raft, the goal is to agree on not just a single value but a series of values over time, forming a progressively-growing history.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] While multi-valued consensus may be achieved naively by running multiple iterations of a single-valued consensus protocol in succession, many optimizations and other considerations such as reconfiguration support can make multi-valued consensus protocols more efficient in practice.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] There are two types of failures a process may undergo, a crash failure or a Byzantine failure.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] A *crash failure* occurs when a process abruptly stops and does not resume.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] *Byzantine failure*s are failures in which absolutely no conditions are imposed.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] For example, they may occur as a result of the malicious actions of an adversary.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] A process that experiences a Byzantine failure may send contradictory or conflicting data to other processes, or it may sleep and then resume activity after a lengthy delay.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Of the two types of failures, Byzantine failures are far more disruptive.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Thus, a consensus protocol tolerating Byzantine failures must be resilient to every possible error that can occur.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] must have been proposed by some correct process.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] The consensus problem may be considered in the case of asynchronous or synchronous systems.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] While real world communications are often inherently asynchronous, it is more practical and often easier to model synchronous systems, given that asynchronous systems naturally involve more issues than synchronous ones.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] In synchronous systems, it is assumed that all communications proceed in *rounds*.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] In one round, a process may send all the messages it requires, while receiving all messages from other processes.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] In this manner, no message from one round may influence any messages sent within the same round.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] In a fully asynchronous message-passing distributed system, in which at least one process may have a *crash failure*, it has been proven in the famous 1985 **FLP impossibility result** by Fischer, Lynch and Paterson that a deterministic algorithm for achieving consensus is impossible.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] This impossibility result derives from worst-case scheduling scenarios, which are unlikely to occur in practice except in adversarial situations such as an intelligent denial-of-service attacker in the network.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] In most normal situations, process scheduling has a degree of natural randomness.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] In an asynchronous model, some forms of failures can be handled by a synchronous consensus protocol.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] For instance, the loss of a communication link may be modeled as a process which has suffered a Byzantine failure.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Randomized consensus algorithms can circumvent the FLP impossibility result by achieving both safety and liveness with overwhelming probability, even under worst-case scheduling scenarios such as an intelligent denial-of-service attacker in the network.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Consensus algorithms traditionally assume that the set of participating nodes is fixed and given at the outset: that is, that some prior (manual or automatic) configuration process has **permissioned** a particular known group of participants who can authenticate each other as members of the group.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] In the absence of such a well-defined, closed group with authenticated members, a Sybil attack against an open consensus group can defeat even a Byzantine consensus algorithm, simply by creating enough virtual participants to overwhelm the fault tolerance threshold.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] A **permissionless** consensus protocol, in contrast, allows anyone in the network to join dynamically and participate without prior permission, but instead imposes a different form of artificial cost or barrier to entry to mitigate the Sybil attack threat.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Motivated in part by the high energy cost of this approach, subsequent permissionless consensus protocols have proposed or adopted other alternative participation rules for Sybil attack protection, such as proof of stake, proof of space, and proof of authority.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Three agreement problems of interest are as follows.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] A collection of n processes, numbered from 0 to $n-1,$ communicate by sending messages to one another.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] 2. for any two correct processes, each process receives the same value.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] It is also known as The General's Problem.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] For *n* processes in a partially synchronous system (the system alternates between good and bad periods of synchrony), each process chooses a private value.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] 2. all messages sent in a round by a correct process are received in the same round by all correct processes (consistency property).
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] It can be shown that variations of these problems are equivalent in that the solution for a problem in one type of model may be the solution for another problem in another type of model.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] For example, a solution to the Weak Byzantine General problem in a synchronous authenticated message passing model leads to a solution for Weak Interactive Consistency.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] An interactive consistency algorithm can solve the consensus problem by having each process choose the majority value in its consensus vector as its consensus value.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] There is a t-resilient anonymous synchronous protocol which solves the Byzantine Generals problem, if ${\tfrac {t}{n}}<{\tfrac {1}{3}}$ and the Weak Byzantine Generals case where t is the number of failures and n is the number of processes.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] For systems with n processors, of which f are Byzantine, it has been shown that there exists no algorithm that solves the consensus problem for $n\leq 3f$ in the *oral-messages model*.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] The proof is constructed by first showing the impossibility for the three-node case $n=3$ and using this result to argue about partitions of processors.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] In the *written-messages model* there are protocols that can tolerate $n=f+1$ .
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] In a fully asynchronous system there is no consensus solution that can tolerate one or more crash failures even when only requiring the non triviality property.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] This result is sometimes called the FLP impossibility proof named after the authors Michael J.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Fischer, Nancy Lynch, and Mike Paterson who were awarded a Dijkstra Prize for this significant work.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] The FLP result has been mechanically verified to hold even under fairness assumptions.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] However, FLP does not state that consensus can never be reached: merely that under the model's assumptions, no algorithm can always reach consensus in bounded time.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] In practice it is highly unlikely to occur.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] The Paxos consensus algorithm by Leslie Lamport, and variants of it such as Raft, are used pervasively in widely deployed distributed and cloud computing systems.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] These algorithms are typically synchronous, dependent on an elected leader to make progress, and tolerate only crashes and not Byzantine failures.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Other protocols, such as Cerberus, have been developed to apply Byzantine fault-tolerant consensus to sharded distributed ledgers and have been the subject of academic analysis.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] An example of a polynomial time binary consensus protocol that tolerates Byzantine failures is the Phase King algorithm by Garay and Berman.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] The algorithm solves consensus in a synchronous message passing model with *n* processes and up to *f* failures, provided *n* > 4*f*.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] In the phase king algorithm, there are *f* + 1 phases, with 2 rounds per phase.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Each process keeps track of its preferred output (initially equal to the process's own input value).
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] In the first round of each phase each process broadcasts its own preferred value to all other processes.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] It then receives the values from all processes and determines which value is the majority value and its count.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] In the second round of the phase, the process whose id matches the current phase number is designated the king of the phase.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] The king broadcasts the majority value it observed in the first round and serves as a tie breaker.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Each process then updates its preferred value as follows.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] If the count of the majority value the process observed in the first round is greater than *n*/2 + *f*, the process changes its preference to that majority value; otherwise it uses the phase king's value.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] At the end of *f* + 1 phases the processes output their preferred values.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Google has implemented a distributed lock service library called Chubby.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Chubby maintains lock information in small files which are stored in a replicated database to achieve high availability in the face of failures.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] The database is implemented on top of a fault-tolerant log layer which is based on the Paxos consensus algorithm.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] In this scheme, Chubby clients communicate with the Paxos *master* in order to access/update the replicated log; i.e., read/write to the files.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Many peer-to-peer online real-time strategy games use a modified lockstep protocol as a consensus protocol in order to manage game state between players in a game.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Each game action results in a game state delta broadcast to all other players in the game along with a hash of the total game state.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Each player validates the change by applying the delta to their own game state and comparing the game state hashes.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Another well-known approach is called MSR-type algorithms which have been used widely in fields from computer science to control theory.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Bitcoin uses proof of work, a difficulty adjustment function and a reorganization function to achieve permissionless consensus in its open peer-to-peer network.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] To extend bitcoin's blockchain or distributed ledger, *miners* attempt to solve a cryptographic puzzle, where probability of finding a solution is proportional to the computational effort expended in hashes per second.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] The node that first solves such a puzzle has their proposed version of the next block of transactions added to the ledger and eventually accepted by all other nodes.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] As any node in the network can attempt to solve the proof-of-work problem, a Sybil attack is infeasible in principle unless the attacker has over 50% of the computational resources of the network.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Ethereum, NEO, STRATIS, ...) use proof of stake, in which nodes compete to append blocks and earn associated rewards in proportion to *stake*, or existing cryptocurrency allocated and locked or *staked* for some time period.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] One advantage of a 'proof of stake' over a 'proof of work' system, is the high energy consumption demanded by the latter.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] As an example, bitcoin mining (2018) is estimated to consume non-renewable energy sources at an amount similar to the entire nations of Czech Republic or Jordan, while the total energy consumption of Ethereum, the largest proof of stake network, is just under that of 205 average US households.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Some cryptocurrencies, such as Ripple, use a system of validating nodes to validate the ledger.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Step 4: the final round requires 80% agreement.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Other participation rules used in permissionless consensus protocols to impose barriers to entry and resist sybil attacks include proof of authority, proof of space, proof of burn, or proof of elapsed time.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Proposed approaches to achieving one-per-person distribution of consensus power for proof of personhood include physical pseudonym parties, social networks, pseudonymized government-issued identities, and biometrics.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] To solve the consensus problem in a shared-memory system, concurrent objects must be introduced.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] A concurrent object, or shared object, is a data structure which helps concurrent processes communicate to reach an agreement.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Traditional implementations using critical sections face the risk of crashing if some process dies inside the critical section or sleeps for an intolerably long time.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Researchers defined wait-freedom as the guarantee that the algorithm completes in a finite number of steps.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] The **consensus number** of a concurrent object is defined to be the maximum number of processes in the system which can reach consensus by the given object in a wait-free implementation.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Objects with a consensus number of n can implement any object with a consensus number of n or lower, but cannot implement any objects with a higher consensus number.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] The consensus numbers form what is called Herlihy's hierarchy of synchronization objects.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] According to the hierarchy, read/write registers cannot solve consensus even in a 2-process system.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] Data structures like stacks and queues can only solve consensus between two processes.
[src:consensus-algorithms/consensus-computer-science] However, some concurrent objects are universal (notated in the table with $\infty$ ), which means they can solve consensus among any number of processes and they can simulate any other objects through an operation sequence.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] In distributed computing, **leader election** is the process of designating a single process as the organizer of some task distributed among several computers (nodes).
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Before the task has begun, all network nodes are either unaware which node will serve as the "leader" (or coordinator) of the task, or unable to communicate with the current coordinator.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] After a leader election algorithm has been run, however, each node throughout the network recognizes a particular, unique node as the task leader.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] The network nodes communicate among themselves in order to decide which of them will get into the "leader" state.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] For that, they need some method in order to break the symmetry among them.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] For example, if each node has unique and comparable identities, then the nodes can compare their identities, and decide that the node with the highest identity is the leader.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] The definition of this problem is often attributed to LeLann, who formalized it as a method to create a new token in a token ring network in which the token has been lost.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Leader election algorithms are designed to be economical in terms of total bytes transmitted, and time.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] The algorithm suggested by Gallager, Humblet, and Spira for general undirected graphs has had a strong impact on the design of distributed algorithms in general, and won the Dijkstra Prize for an influential paper in distributed computing.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Many other algorithms have been suggested for different kinds of network graphs, such as undirected rings, unidirectional rings, complete graphs, grids, directed Euler graphs, and others.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] A general method that decouples the issue of the graph family from the design of the leader election algorithm was suggested by Korach, Kutten, and Moran.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] The problem of leader election is for each processor eventually to decide whether it is a leader or not, subject to the constraint that exactly one processor decides that it is the leader.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] In every execution, exactly one processor becomes elected and the rest determine that they are not elected.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] **Uniqueness**: there is exactly one processor that considers itself as leader.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] **Agreement**: all other processors know who the leader is.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] A ring network is a connected-graph topology in which each node is exactly connected to two other nodes, i.e., for a graph with n nodes, there are exactly n edges connecting the nodes.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] A ring is said to be anonymous if every processor is identical.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] More formally, the system has the same state machine for every processor.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] There is no deterministic algorithm to elect a leader in anonymous rings, even when the size of the network is known to the processes.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] This is due to the fact that there is no possibility of breaking symmetry in an anonymous ring if all processes run at the same speed.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] The state of processors after some steps only depends on the initial state of neighbouring nodes.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] So, because their states are identical and execute the same procedures, in every round the same messages are sent by each processor.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Therefore, each processor state also changes identically and as a result if one processor is elected as a leader, so are all the others.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] For simplicity, here is a proof in anonymous synchronous rings.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Consider an anonymous ring R with size n>1.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Assume there exists an algorithm "A" to solve leader election in this anonymous ring R.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] of the admissible execution of A in R, all the processes have the same states.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] The above lemma contradicts the fact that after some finite number of rounds in an execution of A, one process entered the elected state and other processes entered the non-elected state.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] A common approach to solve the problem of leader election in anonymous rings is the use of probabilistic algorithms.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] In such approaches, generally processors assume some identities based on a probabilistic function and communicate it to the rest of the network.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] At the end, through the application of an algorithm, a leader is selected (with high probability).
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Since there is no algorithm for anonymous rings (proved above), the asynchronous rings would be considered as asynchronous non-anonymous rings.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] In non-anonymous rings, each process has a unique $id$ , and they don't know the size of the ring.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Leader election in asynchronous rings can be solved by some algorithm with using $O(n^{2})$ messages or $O(n\log n)$ messages.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] In the $O(n^{2})$ algorithm, every process sends a message with its $id$ to the left edge.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Then waits until a message from the right edge.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] If the $id$ in the message is greater than its own $id$ , then forwards the message to the left edge; else ignore the message, and does nothing.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] If the $id$ in the message is equal to its own $id$ , then sends a message to the left announcing myself is elected.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Other processes forward the announcement to the left and turn themselves to non-elected.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] It is clear that the upper bound is $O(n^{2})$ for this algorithm.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] In the $O(n\log n)$ algorithm, it is running in phases.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] On the k th phase, a process will determine whether it is the winner among the left side $2^{k}$ and right side $2^{k}$ neighbors.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] If it is a winner, then the process can go to next phase.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] In phase 0 , each process P needs to determine itself is a winner or not by sending a message with its $id$ to the left and right neighbors (neighbor do not forward the message).
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] The neighbor replies an $ACK$ only if the $id$ in the message is larger than the neighbor's $id$ , else replies an $ACK_{fault}$ .
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] If P receives two $ACK$ s, one from the left, one from the right, then P is the winner in phase 0 .
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] In phase k , the winners in phase $k-1$ need to send a message with its $id$ to the $2^{k}$ left and $2^{k}$ right neighbors.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] If the neighbors in the path receive the $id$ in the message larger than their $id$ , then forward the message to the next neighbor, otherwise reply an $ACK_{fault}$ .
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] If the $2^{k}$ th neighbor receives the $id$ larger than its $id$ , then sends back an $ACK$ , otherwise replies an $ACK_{fault}$ .
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] If the process receives two $ACK$ s, then it is the winner in phase k .
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] In the last phase, the final winner will receive its own $id$ in the message, then terminates and send termination message to the other processes.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] In the worst case, each phase there are at most ${\frac {n}{2^{k}+1}}$ winners, where k is the phase number.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] There are $\lceil \log(n-1)\rceil$ phases in total.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Each winner sends in the order of $2^{k}$ messages in each phase.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] So, the messages complexity is $O(n\log n)$ .
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] In Attiya and Welch's Distributed Computing book, they described a non-uniform algorithm using $O(n)$ messages in synchronous ring with known ring size n .
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] The algorithm is operating in phases, each phase has n rounds, each round is one time unit.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] In phase 0 , if there is a process with $id=0$ , then process 0 sends termination message to the other processes (sending termination messages cost n rounds).
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] The algorithm will check if there is a phase number equals to a process $id$ , then does the same steps as phase 0 .
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] At the end of the execution, the minimal $id$ will be elected as the leader.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] It used exactly n messages and $n(minimum\_id+1)$ rounds.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Itai and Rodeh introduced an algorithm for a unidirectional ring with synchronized processes.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] They assume the size of the ring (number of nodes) is known to the processes.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] For a ring of size n, a≤n processors are active.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Each processor decides with probability of a^(-1) whether to become a candidate.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] At the end of each phase, each processor calculates the number of candidates c and if it is equal to 1, it becomes the leader.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] To determine the value of c, each candidate sends a token (pebble) at the start of the phase which is passed around the ring, returning after exactly n time units to its sender.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Every processor determines c by counting the number of pebbles which passed through.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] This algorithm achieves leader election with expected message complexity of O(nlogn).
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] A similar approach is also used in which a time-out mechanism is employed to detect deadlocks in the system.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] There are also algorithms for rings of special sizes such as prime size and odd size.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] In typical approaches to leader election, the size of the ring is assumed to be known to the processes.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] In the case of anonymous rings, without using an external entity, it is not possible to elect a leader.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Even assuming an algorithm exists, the leader could not estimate the size of the ring. i.e. in any anonymous ring, there is a positive probability that an algorithm computes a wrong ring size.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] To overcome this problem, Fisher and Jiang used a so-called leader oracle Ω? that each processor can ask whether there is a unique leader.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] They show that from some point upward, it is guaranteed to return the same answer to all processes.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] In one of the early works, Chang and Roberts proposed a uniform algorithm in which a processor with the highest ID is selected as the leader.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Each processor sends its ID in a clockwise direction.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] A processor receives a message and compares the ID with its own.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] If the ID is bigger than the processor passes it through, otherwise it discards the message.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] The authors show that this algorithm uses $O(n^{2})$ messages in the worst case and $O(n\log n)$ in the average case.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Hirschberg and Sinclair improved this algorithm with $O(n\log n)$ message complexity by introducing a bidirectional message-passing scheme.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] The mesh is another popular form of network topology, especially in parallel systems, redundant memory systems and interconnection networks.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] In a mesh structure, nodes are either corner (only two neighbours), border (only three neighbours) or interior (with four neighbours).
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] The number of edges in a mesh of size a x b is m=2ab-a-b.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] A typical algorithm to solve the leader election in an unoriented mesh is to only elect one of the four corner nodes as the leader.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Since the corner nodes might not be aware of the state of other processes, the algorithm should first wake up the corner nodes.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] *Election process*: the election in outer ring takes two stages at most with $6(a+b)-16$ messages.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] *Termination*: leader sends a terminating message to all nodes.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] The message complexity is at most $6(a+b)-16$ , and if the mesh is square-shaped, $O({\sqrt {n}})$ .
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] An oriented mesh is a special case where port numbers are compass labels, i.e. north, south, east and west.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Leader election in an oriented mesh is trivial.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] "north" and "east" and make sure that node knows it is a leader.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] A special case of mesh architecture is a torus which is a mesh with "wrap-around".
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] In this structure, every node has exactly 4 connecting edges.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] One approach to elect a leader in such a structure is known as electoral stages.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Similar to procedures in ring structures, this method in each stage eliminates potential candidates until eventually one candidate node is left.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] This node becomes the leader and then notifies all other processes of termination.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] This approach can be used to achieve a complexity of O(n).
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] There also more practical approaches introduced for dealing with presence of faulty links in the network.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] A Hypercube $H_{k}$ is a network consisting of $n=2^{k}$ nodes, each with degree of k and $O(n\log n)$ edges.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] A similar electoral stages as before can be used to solve the problem of leader election.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] In each stage two nodes (called duelists) compete and the winner is promoted to the next stage.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] This means in each stage only half of the duelists enter the next stage.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] This procedure continues until only one duelist is left, and it becomes the leader.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Once selected, it notifies all other processes.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] This algorithm requires $O(n)$ messages.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] In the case of unoriented hypercubes, a similar approach can be used but with a higher message complexity of $O(n\log \log n)$ .
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Complete networks are structures in which all processes are connected to one another, i.e., the degree of each node is n-1, n being the size of the network.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] An optimal solution with O(n) message and space complexity is known.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Passive: the initial state of processes before start.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Candidate: the status of nodes after waking up.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] The candidate nodes will be considered to become the leader.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] There is an assumption that although a node does not know the total set of nodes in the system, it is required that in this arrangement every node knows the identifier of its single successor, which is called neighbor, and every node is known by another one.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] All processors initially start in a passive state until they are woken up.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Once the nodes are awake, they are candidates to become the leader.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Based on a priority scheme, candidate nodes collaborate in the virtual ring.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] At some point, candidates become aware of the identity of candidates that precede them in the ring.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] The higher priority candidates ask the lower ones about their predecessors.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] The candidates with lower priority become dummies after replying to the candidates with higher priority.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Based on this scheme, the highest priority candidate eventually knows that all nodes in the system are dummies except itself, at which point it knows it is the leader.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] The above algorithm is not correct — it needs further improvement.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] As the name implies, these algorithms are designed to be used in any process network without prior knowledge of the network's topology or properties (such as size).
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] The Shout protocol builds a spanning tree on a generic graph and elects its root as leader.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] The algorithm has a total cost linear in the edges cardinality.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] This technique is similar to finding a Minimum Spanning Tree (MST) in which the root of the tree becomes the leader.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] The idea is that individual nodes "merge" with each other to form bigger structures.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] The result of this algorithm is a tree (a graph with no cycles) whose root is the leader of the entire system.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] The cost of the mega-merger method is $O(m+n\log n)$ , where m is the number of edges and n is the number of nodes.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Yo-yo (algorithm) is a minimum finding algorithm consisting of two parts: a preprocessing phase and a series of iterations.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] In the first phase or *setup*, each node exchanges its id with all its neighbours and based on the value it orients its incident edges.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] For instance, if node x has a smaller id than y, x orients towards y.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] If a node has a smaller id than all its neighbours it becomes a **source**.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] In contrast, a node with all inward edges (i.e., with id larger than all of its neighbours) is a **sink**.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Once all the edges are oriented, the *iteration* phase starts.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Each iteration is an electoral stage in which some candidates will be removed.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Each iteration has two phases: *YO-* and *–YO*.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] In this phase sources start the process to propagate to each sink the smallest values of the sources connected to that sink.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] An internal node waits to receive a value from all its in-neighbours.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] It calculates the minimum and sends it to out-neighbour.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] A sink (a node with no outgoing edge) receives all the values and compute their minimum.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] An internal node sends YES to all in-neighbours from which it received the smallest value and NO to others.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] If it receives only one NO, it sends NO to all.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] A source waits until it receives all votes.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] If all YES, it survives and if not, it is no longer a candidate.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] When a node x sends NO to an in-neighbour y, the logical direction of that edge is reversed.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] When a node y receives NO from an out-neighbour, it flips the direction of that link.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] After the final stage, any source who receives a NO is no longer a source and becomes a sink.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] An additional stage, *pruning*, also is introduced to remove the nodes that are useless, i.e. their existence has no impact on the next iterations.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] If, in the YO- phase the same value is received by a node from more than one in-neighbour, it will ask all but one to remove the link connecting them.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] This method has a total cost of O(m log n) messages.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Its real message complexity including pruning is an open research problem and is unknown.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] In radio network protocols, leader election is often used as a first step to approach more advanced communication primitives, such as message gathering or broadcasts.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] The very nature of wireless networks induces collisions when adjacent nodes transmit at the same time; electing a leader allows to better coordinate this process.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] While the diameter *D* of a network is a natural lower bound for the time needed to elect a leader, upper and lower bounds for the leader election problem depend on the specific radio model studied.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] In radio networks, the *n* nodes may in every round choose to either transmit or receive a message.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] If *no collision detection* is available, then a node cannot distinguish between silence or receiving more than one message at a time.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Should *collision detection* be available, then a node may detect more than one incoming message at the same time, even though the messages itself cannot be decoded in that case.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] In the *beeping model*, nodes can only distinguish between silence or at least one message via carrier sensing.
[src:consensus-algorithms/leader-election] Known runtimes for single-hop networks range from a constant (expected with collision detection) to *O(n log n)* rounds (deterministic and no collision detection).
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] In computer science, **Paxos** is a family of protocols for solving consensus in a network of unreliable or fallible processors.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Consensus is the process of agreeing on one result among a group of participants.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] This problem becomes difficult when the participants or their communications may experience failures.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Consensus protocols are the basis for the state machine replication approach to distributed computing, as suggested by Leslie Lamport and surveyed by Fred Schneider.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] State machine replication is a technique for converting an algorithm into a fault-tolerant, distributed implementation.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Ad-hoc techniques may leave important cases of failures unresolved.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] The principled approach proposed by Lamport et al. ensures all cases are handled safely.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] The Paxos protocol was first submitted in 1989 and named after a fictional legislative consensus system used on the Paxos island in Greece, where Lamport wrote that the parliament had to function "even though legislators continually wandered in and out of the parliamentary Chamber".
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] It was later published as a journal article in 1998.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] The Paxos family of protocols includes a spectrum of trade-offs between the number of processors, number of message delays before learning the agreed value, the activity level of individual participants, number of messages sent, and types of failures.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Although no deterministic fault-tolerant consensus protocol can guarantee progress in an asynchronous network (a result proved in a paper by Fischer, Lynch and Paterson), Paxos guarantees safety (consistency), and the conditions that could prevent it from making progress are difficult to provoke.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Paxos is usually used where durability is required (for example, to replicate a file or a database), in which the amount of durable state could be large.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] The protocol attempts to make progress even during periods when some bounded number of replicas are unresponsive.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] There is also a mechanism to drop a permanently failed replica or to add a new replica.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] In 1988, Lynch, Dwork and Stockmeyer had demonstrated the solvability of consensus in a broad family of "partially synchronous" systems.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Paxos has similarities to a protocol used for agreement in "viewstamped replication", first published by Oki and Liskov in 1988, in the context of distributed transactions.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Paxos offered an elegant formalism and included one of the earliest proofs of safety for a fault-tolerant distributed consensus protocol.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Reconfigurable state machines have ties to prior work on reliable group multicast protocols that support dynamic group membership e.g.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Birman's work in 1985 and 1987 on the virtually synchronous gbcast protocol. gbcast is uncommon in supporting durability and addressing partitioning failures.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Most reliable multicast protocols do not have these properties which are required for implementations of the state machine replication model.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] This point is discussed in a paper by Lamport, Malkhi and Zhou.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Paxos protocols are members of a theoretical class of solutions to a problem formalized as uniform agreement with crash failures.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Lower bounds for this problem have been proved by Keidar and Shraer.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Derecho, a C++ software library for cloud-scale state machine replication, offers a Paxos protocol that has been integrated with self-managed virtually synchronous membership.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] This protocol matches the Keidar and Shraer optimality bounds and maps efficiently to modern remote DMA (RDMA) datacenter hardware.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] In order to simplify the presentation of Paxos, the following assumptions and definitions are made explicit.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Techniques to broaden the applicability are known in the literature, and are not covered in this article.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] In general, a consensus algorithm can make progress using $n=2F+1$ processors, despite the simultaneous failure of any F processors: in other words, the number of non-faulty processes must be strictly greater than the number of faulty processes.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] However, using reconfiguration, a protocol may be employed which survives any number of total failures as long as no more than F fail simultaneously.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] For Paxos protocols, these reconfigurations can be handled as separate *configurations*.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Only proposed values can be chosen and learned.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] No two distinct learners can learn different values (or there can't be more than one decided value).
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] If value C has been proposed, then eventually learner L will learn some value (if sufficient processors remain non-faulty).
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Note that Paxos is *not* guaranteed to terminate, and thus does not have the liveness property.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] This is supported by the Fischer Lynch Paterson impossibility result (FLP) which states that a consistency protocol can only have two of *safety*, *liveness*, and *fault tolerance*.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] As Paxos's point is to ensure fault tolerance and it guarantees safety, it cannot also guarantee liveness.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] In most deployments of Paxos, each participating process acts in three roles: Proposer, Acceptor and Learner.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] By merging roles, the protocol "collapses" into an efficient client-master-replica style deployment, typical of the database community.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] The benefit of the Paxos protocols (including implementations with merged roles) is the guarantee of its safety properties.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] A typical implementation's message flow is covered in the section Multi-Paxos.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] This protocol is the most basic of the Paxos family.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Each "instance" (or "execution") of the basic Paxos protocol decides on a single output value.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] The protocol proceeds over several rounds.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] A successful round has 2 phases: phase 1 (which is divided into parts *a* and *b*) and phase 2 (also divided into parts *a* and *b*).
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] See below the description of the phases.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Remember that we assume an asynchronous model, so e.g. a processor may be in one phase while another processor may be in another.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] , which must be greater than any number previously used in a Prepare message by this Proposer.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] is not the value to be proposed; it is simply a unique identifier of this initial message by the Proposer.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] A Proposer should not initiate Paxos if it cannot communicate with enough Acceptors to constitute a Quorum.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] The Acceptors wait for a Prepare message from any of the Proposers.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] If *n* is less than or equal to any previous proposal number received by the Acceptor, the Acceptor needn't respond and can ignore the proposal.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] However, for the sake of optimization, sending a denial, or *negative acknowledgement* (*NAK*), response would tell the Proposer that it can stop its attempt to create consensus with proposal *n*.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] message previously sent to the Acceptors).
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] This *Accept* message should be interpreted as a "request", as in "Accept this proposal, please!".
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] message to the Proposer and every Learner (which can typically be the Proposers themselves).
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] receiving Accepted messages from a majority of acceptors, i.e.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] after receiving just the first Accept message.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Else, it can ignore the Accept message or request.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Note that consensus is achieved when a majority of Acceptors accept the same *identifier number* (rather than the same *value*).
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Because each identifier is unique to a Proposer and only one value may be proposed per identifier, all Acceptors that accept the same identifier thereby accept the same value.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] However, the Paxos protocol guarantees that consensus is permanent and the chosen value is immutable.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] In these cases, another round must be started with a higher proposal number.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Notice that a Proposer in Paxos could propose "I am the leader" (or, for example, "Proposer X is the leader").
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Because of the agreement and validity guarantees of Paxos, if accepted by a Quorum, then the Proposer is now known to be the leader to all other nodes.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] This satisfies the needs of leader election because there is a single node believing it is the leader and a single node known to be the leader at all times.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] The following diagrams represent several cases/situations of the application of the Basic Paxos protocol.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Some cases show how the Basic Paxos protocol copes with the failure of certain (redundant) components of the distributed system.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Note that the values returned in the *Promise* message are "null" the first time a proposal is made (since no Acceptor has accepted a value before in this round).
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] In the diagram below, there is 1 Client, 1 Proposer, 3 Acceptors (i.e. the Quorum size is 3) and 2 Learners (represented by the 2 vertical lines).
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] This diagram represents the case of a first round, which is successful (i.e. no process in the network fails).
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] The simplest error cases are the failure of an Acceptor (when a Quorum of Acceptors remains alive) and failure of a redundant Learner.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] In these cases, the protocol requires no "recovery" (i.e. it still succeeds): no additional rounds or messages are required, as shown below (in the next two diagrams/cases).
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] In the following diagram, one of the Acceptors in the Quorum fails, so the Quorum size becomes 2.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] In this case, the Basic Paxos protocol still succeeds.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] In the following case, one of the (redundant) Learners fails, but the Basic Paxos protocol still succeeds.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] In this case, a Proposer fails after proposing a value, but before the agreement is reached.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Specifically, it fails in the middle of the Accept message, so only one Acceptor of the Quorum receives the value.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Meanwhile, a new Leader (a Proposer) is elected (but this is not shown in detail).
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Note that there are 2 rounds in this case (rounds proceed vertically, from the top to the bottom).
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] The most complex case is when multiple Proposers believe themselves to be Leaders.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] For instance, the current leader may fail and later recover, but the other Proposers have already re-selected a new leader.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] The recovered leader has not learned this yet and attempts to begin one round in conflict with the current leader.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] In the diagram below, 4 unsuccessful rounds are shown, but there could be more (as suggested at the bottom of the diagram).
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] In the following case, one Proposer achieves acceptance of value V1 by one Acceptor before failing.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] A new Proposer prepares the Acceptors that never accepted V1, allowing it to propose V2.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Then V2 is accepted by all Acceptors, including the one that initially accepted V1.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] In the following case, one Proposer achieves acceptance of value V1 of one Acceptor before failing.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] This Proposer is able to get one Acceptor to accept V2 before failing.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] A new Proposer finds a majority that includes the Acceptor that has accepted V1, and must propose it.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] The Proposer manages to get two Acceptors to accept it before failing.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] At this point, three Acceptors have accepted V1, but not for the same identifier.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Finally, a new Proposer prepares the majority that has not seen the largest accepted identifier.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] The value associated with the largest identifier in that majority is V2, so it must propose it.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] This Proposer then gets all Acceptors to accept V2, achieving consensus.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] In the following case, one Proposer achieves acceptance of value V1 of two Acceptors before failing.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] A new Proposer may start another round, but it is now impossible for that proposer to prepare a majority that doesn't include at least one Acceptor that has accepted V1.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] As such, even though the Proposer doesn't see the existing consensus, the Proposer's only option is to propose the value already agreed upon.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] New Proposers can continually increase the identifier to restart the process, but the consensus can never be changed.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] A typical deployment of Paxos requires a continuous stream of agreed values acting as commands to a distributed state machine.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] If each command is the result of a single instance of the Basic Paxos protocol, a significant amount of overhead would result.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] If the leader is relatively stable, phase 1 becomes unnecessary.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Thus, it is possible to skip phase 1 for future instances of the protocol with the same leader.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] To achieve this, the round number I is included along with each value which is incremented in each round by the same Leader.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Multi-Paxos reduces the failure-free message delay (proposal to learning) from 4 delays to 2 delays.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] In the following diagram, only one instance (or "execution") of the basic Paxos protocol, with an initial Leader (a Proposer), is shown.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Note that a Multi-Paxos consists of several instances of the basic Paxos protocol.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] In this case, subsequent instances of the basic Paxos protocol (represented by *I+1*) use the same leader, so the phase 1 (of these subsequent instances of the basic Paxos protocol), which consist of the Prepare and Promise sub-phases, is skipped.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Note that the Leader should be stable, i.e. it should not crash or change.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] A common deployment of the Multi-Paxos consists in collapsing the role of the Proposers, Acceptors and Learners to "Servers".
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] So, in the end, there are only "Clients" and "Servers".
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] The following diagram represents the first "instance" of a basic Paxos protocol, when the roles of the Proposer, Acceptor and Learner are collapsed to a single role, called the "Server".
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] In the subsequent instances of the basic Paxos protocol, with the same leader as in the previous instances of the basic Paxos protocol, the phase 1 can be skipped.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] A number of optimisations can be performed to reduce the number of exchanged messages, to improve the performance of the protocol, etc.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] A few of these optimisations are reported below.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] "We can save messages at the cost of an extra message delay by having a single distinguished learner that informs the other learners when it finds out that a value has been chosen.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] messages only to the distinguished learner.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] In most applications, the roles of leader and distinguished learner are performed by the same processor.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] As long as all acceptors in that quorum are working and can communicate with the leader and the learners, there is no need for acceptors not in the quorum to do anything.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] "Acceptors do not care what value is chosen.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] messages to ensure that, despite failures, only a single value can be chosen.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] However, if an acceptor does learn what value has been chosen, it can store the value in stable storage and erase any other information it has saved there.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] message, instead of performing its Phase1b or Phase2b action, it can simply inform the leader of the chosen value.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] messages for either v or its hash from a quorum of acceptors, and at least one of those messages contains v rather than its hash.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] messages that tell it the hash of a value v that it must use in its Phase2a action without telling it the actual value of v.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] "A proposer can send its proposal only to the leader rather than to all coordinators.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] However, this requires that the result of the leader-selection algorithm be broadcast to the proposers, which might be expensive.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] So, it might be better to let the proposer send its proposal to all coordinators.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] messages to the leader and the leader can inform the learners when a value has been chosen.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] However, this adds an extra message delay.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] "Finally, observe that phase 1 is unnecessary for round 1 ..
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Cheap Paxos extends Basic Paxos to tolerate F failures with F+1 main processors and F auxiliary processors by dynamically reconfiguring after each failure.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] This reduction in processor requirements comes at the expense of liveness; if too many main processors fail in a short time, the system must halt until the auxiliary processors can reconfigure the system.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] During stable periods, the auxiliary processors take no part in the protocol.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Fast Paxos generalizes Basic Paxos to reduce end-to-end message delays.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] In Basic Paxos, the message delay from client request to learning is 3 message delays.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Fast Paxos allows 2 message delays, but requires that (1) the system be composed of *3f+ 1* acceptors to tolerate up to *f* faults (instead of the classic 2f+1), and (2) the Client to send its request to multiple destinations.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Intuitively, if the leader has no value to propose, then a client could send an *Accept!* message to the Acceptors directly.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] The Acceptors would respond as in Basic Paxos, sending *Accepted* messages to the leader and every Learner achieving two message delays from Client to Learner.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] If the leader detects a collision, it resolves the collision by sending *Accept!* messages for a new round which are *Accepted* as usual.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] This coordinated recovery technique requires four message delays from Client to Learner.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] The final optimization occurs when the leader specifies a recovery technique in advance, allowing the Acceptors to perform the collision recovery themselves.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Thus, uncoordinated collision recovery can occur in three message delays (and only two message delays if all Learners are also Acceptors).
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Conflicting proposals with coordinated recovery.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Note: the protocol does not specify how to handle the dropped client request.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Conflicting proposals with uncoordinated recovery.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Generalized consensus explores the relationship between the operations of the replicated state machine and the consensus protocol that implements it.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] The main discovery involves optimizations of Paxos when conflicting proposals could be applied in any order. i.e., when the proposed operations are commutative operations for the state machine.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] In such cases, the conflicting operations can both be accepted, avoiding the delays required for resolving conflicts and re-proposing the rejected operations.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] This concept is further generalized into ever-growing sequences of commutative operations, some of which are known to be stable (and thus may be executed).
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] The protocol tracks these sequences ensuring that all proposed operations of one sequence are stabilized before allowing any operation non-commuting with them to become stable.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] In order to illustrate Generalized Paxos, the example below shows a message flow between two concurrently executing clients and a replicated state machine implementing read/write operations over two distinct registers A and B.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Note that in this table indicates operations which are non-commutative.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] In practice, a commute occurs only when operations are proposed concurrently.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Note: message abbreviations differ from previous message flows due to specifics of the protocol, see for a full discussion.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] The above message flow shows us that Generalized Paxos can leverage operation semantics to avoid collisions when the spontaneous ordering of the network fails.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] This allows the protocol to be in practice quicker than Fast Paxos.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] However, when a collision occurs, Generalized Paxos needs two additional round trips to recover.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] This situation is illustrated with operations WriteB and ReadB in the above schema.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] In the general case, such round trips are unavoidable and come from the fact that multiple commands can be accepted during a round.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] This makes the protocol more expensive than Paxos when conflicts are frequent.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Hopefully two possible refinements of Generalized Paxos are possible to improve recovery time.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Paxos may also be extended to support arbitrary failures of the participants, including lying, fabrication of messages, collusion with other participants, selective non-participation, etc.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] These types of failures are called Byzantine failures, after the solution popularized by Lamport.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Fast Byzantine Paxos introduced by Martin and Alvisi removes this extra delay, since the client sends commands directly to the Acceptors.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] The failure scenario is the same for both protocols; Each Learner waits to receive F+1 identical messages from different Acceptors.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] The Derecho C++ Paxos library is an open-source Paxos implementation that explores this option.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] Derecho offers both a classic Paxos, with data durability across full shutdown/restart sequences, and vertical Paxos (atomic multicast), for in-memory replication and state-machine synchronization.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] The Paxos protocols employed by Derecho needed to be adapted to maximize asynchronous data streaming and remove other sources of delay on the leader's critical path.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] So doing enables Derecho to sustain the full bidirectional RDMA data rate.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] In contrast, although traditional Paxos protocols can be migrated to an RDMA network by simply mapping the message send operations to native RDMA operations, doing so leaves round-trip delays on the critical path.
[src:consensus-algorithms/paxos-computer-science] In high-speed RDMA networks, even small delays can be large enough to prevent utilization of the full potential bandwidth.
[src:consensus-algorithms/quorum-distributed-computing] A **quorum** is the minimum number of votes that a distributed transaction has to obtain in order to be allowed to perform an operation in a distributed system.
[src:consensus-algorithms/quorum-distributed-computing] A **quorum**-based technique is implemented to enforce consistent operation in a distributed system.
[src:consensus-algorithms/quorum-distributed-computing] Quorum-based voting can be used as a replica control method, as well as a commit method to ensure transaction atomicity in the presence of network partitioning.
[src:consensus-algorithms/quorum-distributed-computing] In a distributed database system, a transaction could execute its operations at multiple sites.
[src:consensus-algorithms/quorum-distributed-computing] Since atomicity requires every distributed transaction to be atomic, the transaction must have the same fate (commit or abort) at every site.
[src:consensus-algorithms/quorum-distributed-computing] In case of network partitioning, sites are partitioned and the partitions may not be able to communicate with each other.
[src:consensus-algorithms/quorum-distributed-computing] This is where a quorum-based technique comes in.
[src:consensus-algorithms/quorum-distributed-computing] The fundamental idea is that a transaction is executed if the majority of sites vote to execute it.
[src:consensus-algorithms/quorum-distributed-computing] Every site in the system is assigned a vote Vi.
[src:consensus-algorithms/quorum-distributed-computing] Let us assume that the total number of votes in the system is V and the abort and commit quorums are Va and Vc, respectively.
[src:consensus-algorithms/quorum-distributed-computing] Before a transaction commits, it must obtain a commit quorum Vc.
[src:consensus-algorithms/quorum-distributed-computing] The total of at least one site that is prepared to commit and zero or more sites waiting $\geq$ Vc.
[src:consensus-algorithms/quorum-distributed-computing] Before a transaction aborts, it must obtain an abort quorum Va The total of zero or more sites that are prepared to abort or any sites waiting $\geq$ Va.
[src:consensus-algorithms/quorum-distributed-computing] The first rule ensures that a transaction cannot be committed and aborted at the same time.
[src:consensus-algorithms/quorum-distributed-computing] The next two rules indicate the votes that a transaction has to obtain before it can terminate one way or the other.
[src:consensus-algorithms/quorum-distributed-computing] In replicated databases, a data object has copies present at several sites.
[src:consensus-algorithms/quorum-distributed-computing] To ensure serializability, no two transactions should be allowed to read or write a data item concurrently.
[src:consensus-algorithms/quorum-distributed-computing] In case of replicated databases, a quorum-based replica control protocol can be used to ensure that no two copies of a data item are read or written by two transactions concurrently.
[src:consensus-algorithms/quorum-distributed-computing] The quorum-based voting for replica control is due to [Gifford, 1979].
[src:consensus-algorithms/quorum-distributed-computing] Each copy of a replicated data item is assigned a vote.
[src:consensus-algorithms/quorum-distributed-computing] Each operation then has to obtain a *read quorum* (Vr) or a *write quorum* (Vw) to read or write a data item, respectively.
[src:consensus-algorithms/quorum-distributed-computing] The first rule ensures that a data item is not read and written by two transactions concurrently.
[src:consensus-algorithms/quorum-distributed-computing] Additionally, it ensures that a read quorum contains at least one site with the newest version of the data item.
[src:consensus-algorithms/quorum-distributed-computing] The second rule ensures that two write operations from two transactions cannot occur concurrently on the same data item.
[src:consensus-algorithms/quorum-distributed-computing] The two rules ensure that one-copy serializability is maintained.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] Raft is not Byzantine fault tolerant; the nodes trust the elected leader, and the algorithm assumes all participants are trustworthy.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] Raft achieves consensus via an elected leader.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] A server in a raft cluster is either a *leader* or a *follower*, and can be a *candidate* in the precise case of an election (leader unavailable).
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] The leader is responsible for log replication to the followers.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] It regularly informs the followers of its existence by sending a heartbeat message.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] Each follower has a timeout (typically between 150 and 300 ms) in which it expects the heartbeat from the leader.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] The timeout is reset on receiving the heartbeat.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] If no heartbeat is received the follower changes its status to candidate and starts a leader election.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] Raft implements consensus by a leader approach.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] The cluster has one and only one elected leader which is fully responsible for managing log replication on the other servers of the cluster.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] It means that the leader can decide on new entries' placement and establishment of data flow between it and the other servers without consulting other servers.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] A leader leads until it fails or disconnects, in which case surviving servers elect a new leader.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] The consensus problem is decomposed in Raft into two relatively independent subproblems listed down below.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] When the existing leader fails or when the algorithm initializes, a new leader needs to be elected.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] In this case, a new *term* starts in the cluster.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] A term is an arbitrary period of time on the server for which a new leader needs to be elected.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] Each term starts with a leader election.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] If the election is completed successfully (i.e. a single leader is elected) the term keeps going with normal operations orchestrated by the new leader.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] If the election is a failure, a new term starts, with a new election.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] A leader election is started by a *candidate* server.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] A server becomes a candidate if it receives no communication by the leader over a period called the *election timeout*, so it assumes there is no acting leader anymore.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] It starts the election by increasing the term counter, voting for itself as new leader, and sending a message to all other servers requesting their vote.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] A server will vote only once per term, on a first-come-first-served basis.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] If a candidate receives a message from another server with a term number larger than the candidate's current term, then the candidate's election is defeated and the candidate changes into a follower and recognizes the leader as legitimate.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] If a candidate receives a majority of votes, then it becomes the new leader.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] If neither happens, e.g., because of a split vote, then a new term starts, and a new election begins.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] Raft uses a randomized election timeout to ensure that split vote problems are resolved quickly.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] This should reduce the chance of a split vote because servers won't become candidates at the same time: a single server will time out, win the election, then become leader and send heartbeat messages to other servers before any of the followers can become candidates.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] The leader is responsible for the log replication.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] Each client request consists of a command to be executed by the replicated state machines in the cluster.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] After being appended to the leader's log as a new entry, each of the requests is forwarded to the followers as AppendEntries messages.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] In case of unavailability of the followers, the leader retries AppendEntries messages indefinitely, until the log entry is eventually stored by all of the followers.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] Once the leader receives confirmation from half or more of its followers that the entry has been replicated, the leader applies the entry to its local state machine, and the request is considered *committed*.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] This event also commits all previous entries in the leader's log.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] Once a follower learns that a log entry is committed, it applies the entry to its local state machine.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] This ensures consistency of the logs between all the servers through the cluster, ensuring that the safety rule of Log Matching is respected.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] In the case of a leader crash, the logs can be left inconsistent, with some logs from the old leader not being fully replicated through the cluster.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] The new leader will then handle inconsistency by forcing the followers to duplicate its own log.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] To do so, for each of its followers, the leader will compare its log with the log from the follower, find the last entry where they agree, then delete all the entries coming after this critical entry in the follower log and replace it with its own log entries.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] This mechanism will restore log consistency in a cluster subject to failures.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] The first four rules are guaranteed by the details of the algorithm described in the previous section.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] The State Machine Safety is guaranteed by a restriction on the election process.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] This rule is ensured by a simple restriction: a candidate can't win an election unless its log contains all committed entries.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] In order to be elected, a candidate has to contact a majority of the cluster, and given the rules for logs to be committed, it means that every committed entry is going to be present on at least one of the servers the candidates contact.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] Raft determines which of two logs (carried by two distinct servers) is more up-to-date by comparing the index term of the last entries in the logs.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] If the logs have a last entry with different terms, then the log with the later term is more up-to-date.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] If the logs end with the same term, then whichever log is longer is more up-to-date.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] In Raft, the request from a candidate to a voter includes information about the candidate's log.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] If its own log is more up-to-date than the candidate's log, the voter denies its vote to the candidate.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] This implementation ensures the State Machine Safety rule.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] If a follower crashes, *AppendEntries* and *vote* requests sent by other servers will fail.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] Such failures are handled by the servers trying indefinitely to reach the downed follower.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] If the follower restarts, the pending requests will complete.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] If the request has already been taken into account before the failure, the restarted follower will just ignore it.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] Timing is critical in Raft to elect and maintain a steady leader over time, in order to have a perfect availability of the cluster.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] Typical numbers for these values can be 0.5 ms to 20 ms for *broadcastTime*, which implies that the programmer sets the *electionTimeout* somewhere between 10 ms and 500 ms.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] It can take several weeks or months between single server failures, which means the values are sufficient for a stable cluster.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] To address cluster membership change issues that can arise in Raft, the algorithm introduces joint consensus, a transitional configuration phase.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] Once the joint consensus is done (that is, the special Cnew configuration entry is replicated to a majority of Cnew servers' logs), the system fully transitions to the new configuration.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] The cluster leader will stop being leader and return to follower state.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] Specifically, it will continue to replicate log entries, but will not count itself as majorities.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] If a server believes that a current leader exists, any RequestVote RPCs (RPCs to gather votes for a leader election) will be disregarded.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] An extension to Raft is log compaction, where each server takes snapshots of its committed entries and saves it to stable storage, along with the index of its last entry and the term in the snapshotted log.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] The leader occasionally sends its snapshots to servers that are lagging behind in its log.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] When the server receives this snapshot, it will either discard its entire log if it's superseded by the snapshot, or only the entries up to the latest one in the snapshot.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] While Raft aims to be an alternative of Paxos and more understandable than Paxos, several issues arise.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] Raft uses a single leader model, where client requests, reads and writes, and log replications goes through a single leader.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] This means that there is a single point of failure and a bottleneck in performance.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] Furthermore, it does not scale with increasing server workload.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] Raft's membership change system has not been formally verified to be correct.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] This means that implementing it is very risky, as there can be many potential bugs and errors.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] Diego Ongaro, one of the co-authors, has tried to create a formal safety proof, but there are no plans to continue developing it due to how complicated it is.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] In 2014, a safety bug was found relating to single server membership changes.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] Raft, like other consensus algorithms, ensures that there can never be an incorrect result under all non-Byzantine conditions.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] This means that Raft is not a Byzantine fault tolerant algorithm.
[src:consensus-algorithms/raft-algorithm] A 2023 study found that blockchain systems based on Raft are vulnerable to Byzantine attacks because of the lack of authentication on the client side.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] In computer science, **state machine replication** (**SMR**) or **state machine approach** is a general method for implementing a fault-tolerant service by replicating servers and coordinating client interactions with server replicas.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] The approach also provides a framework for understanding and designing replication management protocols.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] In terms of clients and services, each service comprises one or more servers and exports operations that clients invoke by making requests.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Although using a single, centralized server is the simplest way to implement a service, the resulting service can only be as fault tolerant as the processor executing that server.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] If this level of fault tolerance is unacceptable, then multiple servers that fail independently can be used.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Usually, replicas of a single server are executed on separate processors of a distributed system, and protocols are used to coordinate client interactions with these replicas.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] A State Machine begins at the State labeled Start.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Each Input received is passed through the transition and output function to produce a new State and an Output.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] The State is held stable until a new Input is received, while the Output is communicated to the appropriate receiver.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] This discussion requires a State Machine to be **deterministic**: multiple copies of the same State Machine begin in the Start state, and receiving the same Inputs in the same order will arrive at the same State having generated the same Outputs.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Typically, systems based on State Machine Replication voluntarily restrict their implementations to use finite-state machines to simplify error recovery.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Determinism is an ideal characteristic for providing fault-tolerance.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Intuitively, if multiple copies of a system exist, a fault in one would be noticeable as a difference in the State or Output from the others.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] The minimum number of copies needed for fault-tolerance is three; one which has a fault, and two others to whom we compare State and Output.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Two copies are not enough as there is no way to tell which copy is the faulty one.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] A three-copy system can support at most one failure (after which it must repair or replace the faulty copy).
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] If more than one of the copies were to fail, all three States and Outputs might differ, and there would be no way to choose which is the correct one.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] In general, a system which supports F failures must have 2F+1 copies (also called replicas).
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] The extra copies are used as evidence to decide which of the copies are correct and which are faulty.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] All of this deduction pre-supposes that replicas are experiencing only random independent faults such as memory errors or hard-drive crash.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Failures caused by replicas which attempt to lie, deceive, or collude can also be handled by the State Machine Approach, with isolated changes.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Failed replicas are not required to stop; they may continue operating, including generating spurious or incorrect Outputs.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Theoretically, if a failed replica is guaranteed to stop without generating outputs, only F+1 replicas are required, and clients may accept the first output generated by the system.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] No existing systems achieve this limit, but it is often used when analyzing systems built on top of a fault-tolerant layer (Since the fault-tolerant layer provides fail-stop semantics to all layers above it).
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Faults where a replica sends different values in different directions (for instance, the correct Output to some of its fellow replicas and incorrect Outputs to others) are called Byzantine Failures.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Byzantine failures may be random, spurious faults, or malicious, intelligent attacks.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] 2F+1 replicas, with non-cryptographic hashes suffices to survive all non-malicious Byzantine failures (with high probability).
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Malicious attacks require cryptographic primitives to achieve 2F+1 (using message signatures), or non-cryptographic techniques can be applied but the number of replicas must be increased to 3F+1.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Receive client requests, interpreted as Inputs to the State Machine.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Execute Inputs in the chosen order on each server.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Respond to clients with the Output from the State Machine.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Monitor replicas for differences in State or Output.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] The remainder of this article develops the details of this technique.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] The appendix contains discussion on typical extensions used in real-world systems such as Logging, Checkpoints, Reconfiguration, and State Transfer.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] The critical step in building a distributed system of State Machines is choosing an order for the Inputs to be processed.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Since all non-faulty replicas will arrive at the same State and Output if given the same Inputs, it is imperative that the Inputs are submitted in an equivalent order at each replica.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Many solutions have been proposed in the literature.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] A *Visible Channel* is a communication path between two entities actively participating in the system (such as clients and servers).
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] A *Hidden Channel* is a communication path which is not revealed to the system.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Example: client to client channels are usually hidden; such as users communicating over a telephone, or a process writing files to disk which are read by another process.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] When all communication paths are visible channels and no hidden channels exist, a partial global order (**Causal Order**) may be inferred from the pattern of communications.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Causal Order may be derived independently by each server.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Inputs to the State Machine may be executed in Causal Order, guaranteeing consistent State and Output for all non-faulty replicas.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] In open systems, hidden channels are common and a weaker form of ordering must be used.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] An order of Inputs may be defined using a voting protocol whose results depend only on the visible channels.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] The problem of voting for a *single* value by a group of independent entities is called **Consensus**.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] By extension, a *series* of values may be chosen by a series of consensus instances.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] This problem becomes difficult when the participants or their communication medium may experience failures.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Inputs may be ordered by their position in the series of consensus instances (**Consensus Order**).
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Consensus Order may be derived independently by each server.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Inputs to the State Machine may be executed in Consensus Order, guaranteeing consistent State and Output for all non-faulty replicas.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] In some cases additional information is available (such as real-time clocks).
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] In these cases, it is possible to achieve more efficient causal or consensus ordering for the Inputs, with a reduced number of messages, fewer message rounds, or smaller message sizes.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Further optimizations are available when the semantics of State Machine operations are accounted for (such as Read vs Write operations).
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] While classical SMR typically enforces a total ordering of requests, recent research into sharded distributed ledgers demonstrates that a partial ordering is sufficient for consistency when transactions do not conflict.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Graph-based dependency models, such as those utilized in the Cerberus protocol, allow non-conflicting state transitions to occur in parallel across different replicas, overcoming the throughput limitations of a single linear log.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Client requests are interpreted as Inputs to the State Machine, and processed into Outputs in the appropriate order.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Each replica will generate an Output independently.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Non-faulty replicas will always produce the same Output.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Before the client response can be sent, faulty Outputs must be filtered out.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Typically, a majority of the Replicas will return the same Output, and this Output is sent as the response to the client.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] If there is no majority of replicas with the same Output, or if less than a majority of replicas returns an Output, a system failure has occurred.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] The client response must be the unique Output: FAIL.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] The permanent, unplanned compromise of a replica is called a *Failure*.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Proof of failure is difficult to obtain, as the replica may simply be slow to respond, or even lie about its status.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Non-faulty replicas will always contain the same State and produce the same Outputs.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] This invariant enables failure detection by comparing States and Outputs of all replicas.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Typically, a replica with State or Output which differs from the majority of replicas is declared faulty.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] A common implementation is to pass checksums of the current replica State and recent Outputs among servers.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] An Audit process at each server restarts the local replica if a deviation is detected.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Cryptographic security is not required for checksums.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] It is possible that the local server is compromised, or that the Audit process is faulty, and the replica continues to operate incorrectly.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] This case is handled safely by the Output filter described previously (see Sending Outputs).
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] In a system with no failures, the Inputs may be discarded after being processed by the State Machine.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Realistic deployments must compensate for transient non-failure behaviors of the system such as message loss, network partitions, and slow processors.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] One technique is to store the series of Inputs in a log.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] During times of transient behavior, replicas may request copies of a log entry from another replica in order to fill in missing Inputs.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] In general the log is not required to be persistent (it may be held in memory).
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] A persistent log may compensate for extended transient periods, or support additional system features such as Checkpoints, and Reconfiguration.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] If left unchecked a log will grow until it exhausts all available storage resources.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] For continued operation, it is necessary to forget log entries.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] In general a log entry may be forgotten when its contents are no longer relevant (for instance if all replicas have processed an Input, the knowledge of the Input is no longer needed).
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] A common technique to control log size is store a duplicate State (called a **Checkpoint**), then discard any log entries which contributed to the checkpoint.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] This saves space when the duplicated State is smaller than the size of the log.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Checkpoints may be added to any State Machine by supporting an additional Input called **CHECKPOINT**.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Each replica maintains a checkpoint in addition to the current State value.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] When the log grows large, a replica submits the CHECKPOINT command just like a client request.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] The system will ensure non-faulty replicas process this command in the same order, after which all log entries before the checkpoint may be discarded.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] In a system with checkpoints, requests for log entries occurring before the checkpoint are ignored.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Replicas which cannot locate copies of a needed log entry are faulty and must re-join the system (see Reconfiguration).
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Reconfiguration allows replicas to be added and removed from a system while client requests continue to be processed.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Planned maintenance and replica failure are common examples of reconfiguration.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Reconfiguration involves Quitting and Joining.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] When a server detects its State or Output is faulty (see Auditing and Failure Detection), it may selectively exit the system.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Likewise, an administrator may manually execute a command to remove a replica for maintenance.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] A new Input is added to the State Machine called **QUIT**.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] A replica submits this command to the system just like a client request.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] All non-faulty replicas remove the quitting replica from the system upon processing this Input.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] During this time, the replica may ignore all protocol messages.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] If a majority of non-faulty replicas remain, the quit is successful.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] After quitting, a failed server may selectively restart or re-join the system.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Likewise, an administrator may add a new replica to the group for additional capacity.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] A new Input is added to the State Machine called **JOIN**.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] All non-faulty replicas add the joining node to the system upon processing this Input.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] A new replica must be up-to-date on the system's State before joining (see State Transfer).
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] When a new replica is made available or an old replica is restarted, it must be brought up to the current State before processing Inputs (see Joining).
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Logically, this requires applying every Input from the dawn of the system in the appropriate order.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Typical deployments short-circuit the logical flow by performing a State Transfer of the most recent Checkpoint (see Checkpoints).
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] This involves directly copying the State of one replica to another using an out-of-band protocol.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] A checkpoint may be large, requiring an extended transfer period.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] During this time, new Inputs may be added to the log.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] If this occurs, the new replica must also receive the new Inputs and apply them after the checkpoint is received.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Typical deployments add the new replica as an observer to the ordering protocol before beginning the state transfer, allowing the new replica to collect Inputs during this period.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Common deployments reduce state transfer times by sending only State components which differ.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] This requires knowledge of the State Machine internals.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Since state transfer is usually an out-of-band protocol, this assumption is not difficult to achieve.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Compression is another feature commonly added to state transfer protocols, reducing the size of the total transfer.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Paxos requires a single leader to ensure liveness.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] That is, one of the replicas must remain leader long enough to achieve consensus on the next operation of the state machine.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] System behavior is unaffected if the leader changes after every instance, or if the leader changes multiple times per instance.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] The only requirement is that one replica remains leader long enough to move the system forward.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] In general, a leader is necessary only when there is disagreement about which operation to perform, and if those operations conflict in some way (for instance, if they do not commute).
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] When conflicting operations are proposed, the leader acts as the single authority to set the record straight, defining an order for the operations, allowing the system to make progress.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] With Paxos, multiple replicas may believe they are leaders at the same time.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] This property makes Leader Election for Paxos very simple, and any algorithm which guarantees an 'eventual leader' will work.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] A number of researchers published articles on the replicated state machine approach in the early 1980s.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Anita Borg described an implementation of a fault tolerant operating system based on replicated state machines in a 1983 paper, *A Message System Supporting Fault Tolerance*.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Leslie Lamport also proposed the state machine approach, in his 1984 paper on "Using Time Instead of Timeout In Distributed Systems".
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Fred Schneider later elaborated the approach in his paper "Implementing Fault-Tolerant Services Using the State Machine Approach: A Tutorial".
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Ken Birman developed the virtual synchrony model in a series of papers published between 1985 and 1987.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] The primary reference to this work is "Exploiting Virtual Synchrony in Distributed Systems", which describes the Isis Toolkit, a system that was used to build the New York and Swiss Stock Exchanges, French Air Traffic Control System, US Navy AEGIS Warship, and other applications.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Most recently, there has also been the creation of the BFT-SMaRt library, a high-performance Byzantine fault-tolerant state machine replication library developed in Java.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] This library implements a protocol very similar to PBFT's, plus complementary protocols which offer state transfer and on-the-fly reconfiguration of hosts (i.e., JOIN and LEAVE operations).
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] BFT-SMaRt is the most recent effort to implement state machine replication, still being actively maintained.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Raft, a consensus based algorithm, was developed in 2013.
[src:consensus-algorithms/state-machine-replication] Motivated by PBFT, Tendermint BFT was introduced for partial asynchronous networks and it is mainly used for Proof of Stake blockchains.
